<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1889-01-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1889-01-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="193" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d193">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Thompson</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                    the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Port au Prince,
                                    Hayti</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1889-01-16"><hi rend="italic">January</hi> 16, 1889</date>.
                            (Received January 30.)</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 249.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Ossipee</hi>
                        left this harbor 5.50 p.m., yesterday en route for Kingston, Jamaica, taking
                        in tow the steamer <hi rend="italic">Haytien Republic</hi>. The U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Galena</hi> steamed from here at 9 o’clock this evening,
                        bound for Key West, Florida.</p>
                    <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John E. W. Thompson.</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>